                <h2 id="entropy">Part 3: Skill Entropy (The Real Cost)</h2>
                <p>The most dangerous cost is not financial; it is strategic. I call this <strong>Skill Entropy</strong>.</p>
                <p><strong>Definition:</strong> <em>The decay of professional value caused by engaging in non-compounding labor.</em></p>
                <p>If you code for 8 hours, you get paid AND you get better at coding. Your rate next year might go up.</p>
                <p>If you drive for 8 hours, you simply get tired. Your driving skill does not compound into higher wages. In fact, you are strictly <strong>financing your own obsolescence</strong>.</p>

